{
  "doc_id": "28471",
  "text": "Idiopathic macular hole (MH) is an important cause of central visual loss [CITATION_1] characterized by a round full-thickness defect in the center of the macular area involving the anatomical fovea [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . e estimated prevalence in the general population is approximately 3.3 per 1000 people [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , with a cumulative incidence of MH formation of 41.1 cases per 100 000 person/ years [CITATION_6] . is incidence increases with age, and the disease usually affects individuals in their sixth or seventh decade of life [CITATION_7] . Females have a 64% increased risk of being diagnosed with MH when compared with males [CITATION_8] . MH is a common complication in pathological myopic eyes with an axial length greater than 26.5 mm and/or a refraction greater than −6.00 diopters [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] , and a prevalence of 8.4% has been reported [CITATION_11] . e incidence of myopic MH is greater in Asian ethnicity compared to Caucasian or black individuals due to the high prevalence of myopic refractive defect in Asian population [CITATION_12] .",
